2star  aThe chapters in this volume build on a growing body of ethnomethodological conversation analytic research on teaching in order to enhance our empirical understandings of teaching as embodied, contingent and jointly achieved with students in the complex management of various courses of action and larger instructional projects. Together, the chapters document the embodied accomplishment of teaching by identifying specific resources that teachers use to manage instructional projects; demonstrate that teaching entails both alignment and affiliation work; and show the significance of using high-quality audiovisual data to document the sophisticated work of teaching. By providing analytic insight into the highly-specialized work of teaching, the studies make a significant contribution to a practice-based understanding of how the life of the classroom, as lived by its members, is accomplished.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aInteraction analysis in education. 7aEDUCATION / Teaching Methods & Materials / General.2bisacsh  aAffiliation.  aAlignment.  aConversation Analysis.  aEMCA.  aEmbodiment.  aEthnomethodology.  aTeaching.1 aBox, DiFelice, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarpenter, Lauren B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDobs, Abby Mueller, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFagan, Drew S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHall, Joan Kelly, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHall, Joan Kelly, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKim, Jamie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKimura, Daisuke, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLooney,